Certainly! Below is an example of a mobile-friendly web app with five buttons that perform simple actions. All the code is contained in a single HTML file with embedded CSS and JavaScript.

```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8">
    <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
    <title>Simple Mobile App</title>
    <style>
        body {
            font-family: Arial, sans-serif;
            margin: 0;
            padding: 0;
            background-color: #f0f0f0;
        }
        header {
            background-color: #4CAF50;
            color: white;
            text-align: center;
            padding: 10px 0;
        }
        .container {
            display: flex;
            flex-direction: column;
            justify-content: center;
            align-items: center;
            height: 100vh;
        }
        button {
            width: 80%;
            padding: 15px;
            margin: 10px;
            font-size: 18px;
            cursor: pointer;
            border: none;
            border-radius: 5px;
            transition: background-color 0.3s;
        }
        button:hover {
            opacity: 0.8;
        }
        .btn1 { background-color: #FF5733; color: white; }
        .btn2 { background-color: #33FF57; color: black; }
        .btn3 { background-color: #3357FF; color: white; }
        .btn4 { background-color: #F1C40F; color: black; }
        .btn5 { background-color: #9B59B6; color: white; }
    </style>
</head>
<body>
    <header>
        <h1>Simple Mobile App</h1>
    </header>
    <div class="container">
        <button class="btn1" onclick="action1()">Button 1: Alert</button>
        <button class="btn2" onclick="action2()">Button 2: Change Color</button>
        <button class="btn3" onclick="action3()">Button 3: Log Time</button>
        <button class="btn4" onclick="action4()">Button 4: Show Message</button>
        <button class="btn5" onclick="action5()">Button 5: Navigate</button>
    </div>

    <script>
        function action1() {
            alert('Hello from Button 1!');
        }

        function action2() {
            document.body.style.backgroundColor = document.body.style.backgroundColor === 'lightblue' ? '#f0f0f0' : 'lightblue';
        }

        function action3() {
            console.log('Current time is: ' + new Date().toLocaleTimeString());
        }

        function action4() {
            alert('This is Button 4 speaking!');
        }

        function action5() {
            window.location.href = 'https://www.example.com';
        }
    </script>
</body>
</html>
```

### How it Works:

- **HTML Structure**: Contains a header and a container for buttons.
- **CSS Styles**: Simple styling for the app, including a responsive design, button styles, and hover effects.
- **JavaScript Functions**:
    - `action1()`: Shows an alert box.
    - `action2()`: Toggles background color between `lightblue` and the default color.
    - `action3()`: Logs the current time in the console.
    - `action4()`: Displays a message box.
    - `action5()`: Navigates to a specified URL when clicked (example.com).

You can copy the entire code block into an HTML file and open it in a web browser to see it in action!
